<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Students 'Go Green' To Win Green: Scholarships Offered In Energy-Saving Competition</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Christine Dellert and Stacey Radnor
		
		<span class="date">Feb. 1, 2008</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="http://news.ucf.edu/resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1314/en_US/energy comp crop.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: UCF News File</p>
			
			<p>Shaina Duffey turns off the power strip on her desk at the Lake Claire residence hall. Shutting off computers when they're not in use is one way that students can help to conserve energy.
</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004144fcb4b10117ade51f2a007671">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:sradnor@mail.ucf.edu">Stacey Radnor, Center for Energy and Sustainability</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-4039</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cdellert@mail.ucf.edu">Christine Dellert, News and Information</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-2947</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://energy.ucf.edu">UCF Center for Energy and Sustainability</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Turn off a light switch and win money for college?</p>
<p>It might sound too good to be true. But starting today, on-campus residents at the University of Central Florida are competing to see who can save the most energy at home.</p>
<p>Those who do could receive free food, gift certificates and thousands of dollars in scholarships.</p>
<p>It&rsquo;s all part of the second-annual Energy Conservation Competition -- a monthlong campaign that challenges each residence hall to reduce its electric consumption by the greatest percentage compared to previous years.</p>
<p>Students last year slashed their energy use by 8 percent -- enough to power 115 homes for a month or the equivalent of $12,000 in electric bills.</p>
<p>UCF&rsquo;s Center for Energy and Sustainability and Housing and Residence Life, the competition&rsquo;s organizers, are hoping for even larger consumption cuts this year.</p>
<p>&quot;Taking steps to conserve energy only takes a minute, and we&rsquo;re excited about this opportunity to educate our students and staff on the importance of conservation,&quot; said Vernon Rogers, an area coordinator with Housing and Residence Life. &quot;We hope that, through our efforts, we can set an example for the UCF community.&quot;</p>
<p>About 5,700 students who live on UCF&rsquo;s main campus are involved. And organizers expanded this year&rsquo;s competition to include two residence halls that house about 350 students at the Rosen College of Hospitality Management campus near International Drive.</p>
<p>The competition runs through the end of February and will compare energy consumption with a baseline average of the previous three years.</p>
<p>Winners will be announced in March and could receive scholarships from the Student Government Association. UCF officials expect to divide $6,000 in scholarship awards among the top energy conservers in each winning hall.</p>
<p>&quot;We knew that the opportunity to win scholarships would encourage students to save energy,&quot; said SGA Scholarship Chair Victoria Manglardi. &quot;We are eager to see how much energy the students will conserve, as we know they will all do an excellent job.&quot;</p>
<p>Others in the winning buildings could receive gift certificates to Best Buy and Wackadoo&rsquo;s and a pizza party.</p>
<p>Throughout February, students also will host programs in their buildings that focus on environmental change and energy conservation.</p>
<p>&quot;The Energy Conservation Competition serves as an exciting social marketing campaign that we have employed throughout the university,&quot; said Stacey Radnor, the marketing specialist with UCF&rsquo;s Center for Energy and Sustainability. &quot;Most importantly, it gets the students involved with actions they can take to become better stewards of the environment. It&rsquo;s our hope that those habits will stay with them when they leave UCF.&quot;</p>
<p>To learn more about the competition, visit <a href="http://www.sustainable.ucf.edu">http://www.sustainable.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
<p>Students are encouraged to follow these energy-saving tips:</p>
<p>-- Turn off all lights when leaving the room. Make sure bathroom lights and additional room lighting is kept off when not in use.</p>
<p>-- Use fluorescent bulbs for any additional lamps you bring into your room -- they last seven times longer than an incandescent bulb and use one-fourth of the energy.</p>
<p>-- Open the blinds in your room and use natural sunlight to light your room.</p>
<p>-- Keep all appliances off when not in use.&nbsp; This includes printers, stereos, etc.</p>
<p>-- Unplug other items when not in use. Even cell phone chargers plugged into the wall and not in use still consumes energy.</p>
<p>-- Set computers to sleep mode and turn off monitors when not in use.</p>
<p>-- Keep windows closed when running air-conditioning.</p>
<p>-- Cut down on the number of mini-refrigerators on campus -- share with a friend. Refrigerators should be kept on a low setting and shut properly.</p>
<p>-- When leaving a room, turn up the thermostat five degrees.</p>
<p>-- Remind friends to partake in energy conservation measures everyday.</p>
<p>Do you have any other tips to save energy on campus? Send your ideas to <a href="mailto:energy@ucf.edu">energy@ucf.edu</a>.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands for Opportunity:</strong> Established in 1963, the University of Central Florida is a diverse metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th-largest in the country with more than 48,000 students. Located in Orlando, Fla., UCF offers high-quality undergraduate and graduate education, student development and continuing education, while conducting cutting-edge research that powers the region's economic development. For more UCF news, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
